<p class="p">A physically more meaningful and more relevant quantity for risk assessment is the probability of the variable (here, multi-day extreme precipitation and discharge) exceeding a certain level. The precipitation and discharge of annual maximum series under given return periods were calculated based on the generalized extreme value (GEV) distribution, which is widely utilized in modeling extreme events in meteorology and hydrology [
 <xref rid="B19-ijerph-15-02491" ref-type="bibr" class="xref">19</xref>]. Equations (2) and (3) are the distribution function:
 <disp-formula id="FD2-ijerph-15-02491" class="disp-formula">
  <label class="label">(2)</label>
  <math id="mm2" class="math">
   <mrow class="mrow">
    <mtable columnalign="left" class="mtable">
     <mtr class="mtr">
      <mtd class="mtd">
       <mi class="mi">F</mi>
       <mrow class="mrow">
        <mo class="mo">(</mo>
        <mi class="mi">x</mi>
        <mo class="mo">)</mo>
       </mrow>
       <mo class="mo">=</mo>
       <mi class="mi">exp</mi>
       <mrow class="mrow">
        <mo class="mo">{</mo>
        <mrow class="mrow">
         <mo class="mo">−</mo>
         <msup class="msup">
          <mrow class="mrow">
           <mrow class="mrow">
            <mo class="mo">[</mo>
            <mrow class="mrow">
             <mn class="mn">1</mn>
             <mo class="mo">+</mo>
             <mi class="mi">k</mi>
             <mrow class="mrow">
              <mo class="mo">(</mo>
              <mrow class="mrow">
               <mfrac class="mfrac">
                <mrow class="mrow">
                 <mi class="mi">x</mi>
                 <mo class="mo">−</mo>
                 <mi class="mi">ξ</mi>
                </mrow>
                <mi class="mi">α</mi>
               </mfrac>
              </mrow>
              <mo class="mo">)</mo>
             </mrow>
            </mrow>
            <mo class="mo">]</mo>
           </mrow>
          </mrow>
          <mrow class="mrow">
           <mo class="mo">−</mo>
           <mfrac class="mfrac">
            <mn class="mn">1</mn>
            <mi class="mi">k</mi>
           </mfrac>
          </mrow>
         </msup>
        </mrow>
        <mo class="mo">}</mo>
       </mrow>
       <mo class="mo">,</mo>
       <mi class="mi">k</mi>
       <mo class="mo">≠</mo>
       <mn class="mn">0</mn>
      </mtd>
     </mtr>
     <mtr class="mtr">
      <mtd class="mtd">
       <mi class="mi">F</mi>
       <mrow class="mrow">
        <mo class="mo">(</mo>
        <mi class="mi">x</mi>
        <mo class="mo">)</mo>
       </mrow>
       <mo class="mo">=</mo>
       <mi class="mi">exp</mi>
       <mrow class="mrow">
        <mo class="mo">{</mo>
        <mrow class="mrow">
         <mo class="mo">−</mo>
         <mi class="mi">exp</mi>
         <mrow class="mrow">
          <mo class="mo">[</mo>
          <mrow class="mrow">
           <mo class="mo">−</mo>
           <mrow class="mrow">
            <mo class="mo">(</mo>
            <mrow class="mrow">
             <mfrac class="mfrac">
              <mrow class="mrow">
               <mi class="mi">x</mi>
               <mo class="mo">−</mo>
               <mi class="mi">ξ</mi>
              </mrow>
              <mi class="mi">α</mi>
             </mfrac>
            </mrow>
            <mo class="mo">)</mo>
           </mrow>
          </mrow>
          <mo class="mo">]</mo>
         </mrow>
        </mrow>
        <mo class="mo">}</mo>
       </mrow>
       <mo class="mo">,</mo>
       <mi class="mi">k</mi>
       <mo class="mo">=</mo>
       <mn class="mn">0</mn>
      </mtd>
     </mtr>
    </mtable>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </disp-formula> where, 
 <italic class="italic">ξ</italic>, 
 <italic class="italic">α</italic> and 
 <italic class="italic">k</italic> are parameters standing for location, scale and shape, respectively. In this study, the parameters were estimated by using the Maximum Likelihood Estimation method [
 <xref rid="B39-ijerph-15-02491" ref-type="bibr" class="xref">39</xref>].
</p>
